{{distinguish|Salt of the earth (disambiguation){{!}}Salt of the earth|Salting (confidence trick)}}
{{about|the symbolic practice|salt in the soil|Soil salinity}}
{{for|Wikipedia's page creation protection|Wikipedia:SALT|selfref=yes}}

'''Salting the earth''', or '''sowing with salt''', is the ritual of spreading [[Sodium chloride|salt]] on conquered cities to symbolize a curse on their re-inhabitation.<ref>Ridley, 1986, p. 144.</ref><ref name="Gevritz">Gevirtz, 1963.</ref> It originated as a symbolic practice in the ancient [[Near East]] and became a well-established [[folkloric]] motif in the [[Middle Ages]].<ref>Stevens, 1988.</ref>

==Destroying cities==
The custom of purifying or consecrating a destroyed city with salt and cursing anyone who dared to rebuild it was widespread in the [[ancient Near East]], but historical accounts are unclear as to what the sowing of salt meant in that process.{{cn|date=November 2018|reason=wikipedians themselves cannot claim something is unknown; you need a ref whaichsays this}}

Various [[Hittite language|Hittite]] and [[Assyria]]n texts speak of ceremonially strewing salt, minerals, or plants ([[weed]]s, "cress", or ''kudimmu'', which are associated with salt and desolation<ref>Weinfeld, Moshe. ''Deuteronomy and the Deuteronomic School'', 1992, {{ISBN|0-931464-40-4}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7vSnbQKLyCYC&pg=PA110&dq=kudimmu p. 110]</ref>) over destroyed cities, including [[Hattusa]], [[Taite|Taidu]], [[Arinna]], [[Hunusa]],<ref name="Gevritz"/> [[Irridu]],<ref>Chavalas, Mark. ''The ancient Near East: historical sources in translation'' pp. 144-5.</ref> and [[Susa]].<ref>''Persians: Masters of Empire'', by the editors of [[Time-Life]] Books. Alexandria, Va.: Time-Life Books, 1995. {{ISBN|0-8094-9104-4}} pp. 7-8.</ref> The ''[[Book of Judges]]'' (9:45) says that [[Abimelech (Judges)|Abimelech]], the [[Biblical judges|judge]] of the [[Israelite]]s, sowed his own capital, [[Shechem]], with salt, c. 1050 BC, after quelling a revolt against him. This may have been part of a [[Herem (war or property)|ḥērem]] ritual<ref name="Gevritz"/> (see [[Salt in the Bible]]).

Starting in the 19th century,<ref>{{cite book |author= Ripley, George |authorlink= George Ripley (transcendentalist) |author2=[[Charles Anderson Dana]]  |title= The New American Cyclopædia: a Popular Dictionary of General Knowledge |volume=4 |page=39 |year= 1863 |url= https://archive.org/stream/americancyclopae04ripl#page/38/mode/2up}}</ref> various texts claim that the [[Roman Republic|Roman]] general [[Scipio Aemilianus Africanus]] plowed over and sowed the city of [[Carthage]] with salt after defeating it in the [[Third Punic War]] (146 BC), sacking it, and [[slavery|enslaving]] the survivors.  Though ancient sources do mention symbolically drawing a plow over various cities, and salting them, none mention Carthage in particular.<ref>Stevens, 1988, pp. 39-40.</ref> The Carthage story is a later invention, probably modeled on the story of [[Shechem]].<ref>Ridley, 1986</ref>

When [[Boniface VIII|Pope Boniface VIII]] destroyed [[Palestrina]] in 1299, he ordered that it be plowed "following the old example of Carthage in Africa", and also salted.<ref>Warmington, 1988</ref> "I have run the plough over it, like the ancient Carthage of Africa, and I have had salt sown upon it...."<ref>{{cite book |author=Sedgwick, Henry Dwight |authorlink= Henry Dwight Sedgwick |title=Italy In The Thirteenth Century, Part Two |year=2005 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing, LLC |page=324 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iAogBss02bIC |isbn=978-1-4179-6638-7 }}</ref> The text is not clear as to whether he thought Carthage was salted. Later accounts of other saltings in the destructions of medieval Italian cities are now rejected as unhistorical: [[Padua]] by [[Attila]] (452), perhaps in a parallel between Attila and the ancient Assyrians; [[Milan]] by [[Frederick Barbarossa]] (1162); and [[Semifonte]] by the [[Florence|Florentines]] (1202).<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=2855837 |pages=429–450 |last1=Oerter |first1=H. L. |title=Campaldino, 1289 |volume=43 |issue=3 |journal=Speculum |year=1968 |doi=10.2307/2855837}}</ref>

The English epic poem ''[[Siege of Jerusalem (poem)|Siege of Jerusalem]]'' (c. 1370) recounts that [[Titus]] commanded the sowing of salt on the [[Temple in Jerusalem|Temple]],<ref>Hanna, Ralph and David Lawton, eds., ''The Siege of Jerusalem'', 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=N_Ia3C6eMzgC&pg=PA88 line 1295]</ref> but this episode is not found in [[Josephus]].

==Punishing traitors==

[[File:Padrão do Chão Salgado.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Stone memorial to the [[Duke of Aveiro]]'s punishment in [[Santa Maria de Belém]], [[Lisbon]]. ]]
In [[Spain]] and the [[Spanish Empire]], salt was poured onto the land owned by a convicted traitor (often one who was executed and their head placed on a ''picota'', or pike, afterwards) after their house was demolished.

This was done in [[Portugal]] as well. The last known event of this sort was the destruction of the [[Duke of Aveiro]]'s palace in [[Lisbon]] in 1759, due to his participation in the [[Távora affair]] (a conspiracy against King [[Joseph I of Portugal]]). His palace was demolished and his land was salted.<ref>Joseph Hughes, ''An authentick letter from Mr. Hughes, a Gentleman residing at Lisbon...'', London 1759, [https://books.google.com/books?id=hmNZAAAAcAAJ&q=salt p. 25]</ref> A stone memorial now perpetuates the memory of the shame of the Duke, where it is written:
<blockquote>In this place were put to the ground and salted the houses of José Mascarenhas, stripped of the honours of Duque de Aveiro and others.... Put to Justice as one of the leaders of the most barbarous and execrable upheaval that... was committed against the most royal and sacred person of the Lord Joseph I. In this infamous land nothing may be built for all time.</blockquote>

In the Portuguese [[Colonial Brazil|colony of Brazil]], the leader of the [[Inconfidência Mineira]], [[Tiradentes]], was sentenced to death and his house was "razed and salted, so that never again be built up on the floor, ... and even the floor will rise up a standard by which the memory is preserved (preserving) the infamy of this heinous offender..."<ref name="ws">{{cite wikisource |title=Sentença proferida contra os réus do levante e conjuração de Minas Gerais |wslink=pt:Sentença proferida contra os réus do levante e conjuração de Minas Gerais |year=1789|location=Brazil |language=Portuguese}}</ref> He suffered further indignities, being [[hanged]] and quartered, his body parts carried to various parts of the country where his fellow revolutionaries had met, and his children deprived of their property and honor.<ref name="ws" /><ref>{{cite book |last= Southey |first= Robert |authorlink= Robert Southey |title= History of Brazil |volume= 3 |location= London |publisher= Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown |year= 1819 |page= 684}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Worcester |first= Donald E. |title= Brazil, From Colony to World Power |location= New York |publisher= Scribner |year= 1973 |page= 52 |isbn= 0-684-13386-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Bishop |first= Elizabeth |title= Brazil |location= New York |publisher= Time |year= 1962 |page= 31}}</ref>

==Legends==

An ancient legend says that [[Odysseus]] [[feigned madness]] by yoking a horse and an ox to his plow and sowing salt.<ref>The story does not appear in [[Homer]], but was apparently mentioned in [[Sophocles]]' lost tragedy ''The Mad Ulysses'': [[James George Frazer]], ''ed.'', ''Apollodorus: [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|The Library]]'', '''II''':[https://books.google.com/books?id=hDhgAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA177&dq=sowed%20salt 176 footnote 2]; [[Hyginus]], [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusFabulae2.html#95 ''Fabulae'' '''95'''] mentions the mismatched animals but not the salt.</ref>
